This single form is the operational proof of NFR-SCAL-02's requirement that adding a laboratory

This single form is the operational proof of NFR-SCAL-02's requirement that adding a laboratory

requires no schema or architecture change: every eld maps to an existing database column or

optional conguration value, and creating a lab here does not require touching the AI service, the

rmware, or the database schema. It requires only lling in this form and pairing one physical

ESP32 with the resulting device key. The Create lab button triggers a POST to the /api/labs

endpoint with the form values serialised as JSON; the Cancel button discards the form and navigates

back to the Labs list.


\subsection{Devices  Hardware Registry}
% --- FIGURE PLACEHOLDER: Figure 5.3 ---
\begin{figure}[htbp]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{ch05/figures/devices-page.png}
	\caption{Devices: read-side registry showing Esp32-Lab-D7 Active at 192}
	\label{fig:5-3}
\end{figure}

Figure 5.3: Devices: read-side registry showing Esp32-Lab-D7 Active at 192.168.1.7.

The Devices screen (Figure 5.3) is the read side of the provisioning step. Once a lab has been

created and a device key issued, the corresponding ESP32 appears here with ve data columns: LAB

(Lab D7), DEVICE (Esp32-Lab-D7), TYPE (ESP32 Controller), IP (192.168.1.7), and STATUS

(Active). The Active status is maintained by the rmware's token lifecycle described in Section 5.2.4

a device that fails to authenticate or stops sending events will have its status ipped to Inactive

by the backend after a congurable idle timeout.

The IP address 192.168.1.7 matches the serverUrl, lightApi, and TokenGen constants em-

bedded in the rmware source (Listing 5.3). This screen is therefore the backend's own evidence

that the rmware is successfully reaching the correct host  if the IP were wrong, the rmware's

token exchange would fail, the device would never authenticate, and the Status column would show

Inactive rather than Active.


